figgy.title: Redesign the preservation status indicators on the resource show page

comments.body:
For the first part of this ticket, here's an idea. Thoughts?

![resource-fixity.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5cba15f2e89c9c3b0c58e0d1/d92023a7-51b7-4dbb-9078-0443dd915127)

I was looking for our Preservation Policy, to make sure that it's reflected in this design as per the goals of this ticket, but I can't find it. Do we have a Preservation Policy? I was particularly interested in whether the Local and Cloud fixity are run simultaneously for a resource, or if they are independent and randomized (i.e., cloud fixity is run, but local may not be checked for quite some time or at all, and vice-versa).

I'm not sure about a Preservation Policy. But the checks are run independently. For cloud fixity we run a random selection of resources per day. For local fixity we (plan to) run the least-recently-checked file sets as continuously as we can.

For this design, I like that it adds more language to explain what the numbers mean. I also like that the icons give a more wholistic sense of the status. I like the addition of the link to repair. I'm not entirely sure about the use of the word "originals" here. And from both an implementation and a user standpoint, I don't know exactly what this date means, since the files may have been checked on different dates. It may help to have what you called a Preservation Policy, or just user-facing documentation of how we check fixity.

comments.body: What are non-primary files? The UI should probably indicate that we are intentionally not preserving them, right? And how do I get to this screen? I can't seem to figure out where it exists.

There's one primary file per file set, determined by the following algorithm: https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/7d4a77a9e94c88e58bc4f9915b53bb770f73a816/app/models/file_set.rb#L94-L102

Any other file on that file set is non-primary. Yes, I agree we should make it clear that they're intentionally not preserved.

To get to a file set show page from any resource, click on "file manager" and then select one of the edit / popout icons on one of the files in the list (top right corner of each file card).

Try moving fallback logic from wayfinder into the custom query. Use a right outer join to get both the current event and the value of the primary file's fixity status. then select the right row conditionally (the event if it exists, otherwise the other one) and count them.

This will be blocked on #5589

lae-blacklight.title: Genre/Format is no longer displaying in LAE site for items

comments.body:
From the logs (see https://lib-jobs.princeton.edu/data_sets/5026), it looks like an attempt is being made to process the renewals, but the items aren't found. Perhaps code is pointing to the Alma sandbox?

It looks like I also need to update the URL in the partner parameters to be https://lib-jobs.princeton.edu/ncip-renew.

- It looks like 12/4/2022 was the last time an item was successfully renewed through the renew job
- I'm not sure where the url https://lib-jobs.princeton.edu/ncip-renew comes from? I'm not seeing anything in the application or its history to show that was ever a valid path? (I could always be missing something, but I'm not seeing it). The job is usually triggered via a cron job that calls a rake task, not anything via the UI. 
- I know @christinach was running into issues with the swagger UI and SCSB - I am curious if the timeline matches that issue?

The issue seems to be not involving SCSB, since the renewals are for items that are in Alma (partner items get put into Alma). It's possible the URL doesn't actually do anything, but it's a value that is in the Alma UI for resource sharing partners.

But lib-jobs uses the NCIP protocol to process renewals that are captured by Alma Analytics. So I'm wondering what endpoint lib-jobs is using for those NCIP messages.

I believe it has been using https://princeton.alma.exlibrisgroup.com/view/NCIPServlet as the endpoint. 

I believe the response from the endpoint for each of the non-renewed items is just "Unknown Item". I've looked for the barcodes in Alma and they appear to be present as Location: "Borrowing Resource Sharing Requests" (see, e.g., barcode CU56955006; barcode 33433099769956)

Between the working and non-working runs of this rake task (12/4 - 12/5), the headers on the CSV built by Alma changed from `Barcode,Patron Group,Expiry Date,Primary Identifier` to `Barcode,Patron Group,Expiry Date,User Primary Identifier`, meaning that all the user_id's were not set.

I have updated the headers for the CSV, so we will see if that makes it work when this runs the next time. If it does, will it work if I manually modify all the files generated since 12/4 to fix the header and then remove `.processed` from each filename?

> I have updated the headers for the CSV, so we will see if that makes it work when this runs the next time. If it does, will it work if I manually modify all the files generated since 12/4 to fix the header and then remove `.processed` from each filename?

Yes, I believe if you modified those files to correct the header and remove the `.processed`, then they would be processed correctly the next time the rake task was run, either by the cron job, or by a developer.

comments.body:
For context, this comment is in `edit_work_utils.js`:

> This is an interim solution: My sense is that jQuery doesn't work well with Vite and Turbolinks.
> 
> The standard approach would be
> - vite_javascript_tag,
> - active on every page of the application,
> - and hooks that don't assume the element is already on the page.
> 
> We considered running this for every page of the application, but it causes test failures:
> some of the jQuery hooks interfere with the operation of other pages.
> 
> Turbolinks means that we don't get the expected page-load event,
> so the hooks aren't registered on successive visits to the page.
> 
> Vite wraps it as an ESM, and there doesn't seem to be a way to specify
> an export that we can call as-needed.
